title: Executive Director

She has been recognised by Yahoo Finance and Involve People as #28 of the Top 100 Ethnic Minority Executives #EMPower list (2022) across all industries and sectors globally; awarded title of Pride of India by NRI World across 100+ countries (2022), Advocate of the Year for Diversity and Inclusion (2021) by Morgan Stanley and Digital Leader of the Year (2021) by Seamless Middle East and Terrapin under the patronage of HH Sheikh Saif Bin Zayad Al Nahyan; In 2021, Bijna was named #40 of the Top 100 Women Executives (2021) and as one of the Top 100 Ethnic Minority Executives (2021) across all industries and sectors globally.

Bijna is an appointed Member of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (2020) by Her Majesty, The Queen for her services to Diversity and Inclusion in Financial Services.

Bijna was named Britain’s Rising Star, UK Women of Inspiration awards (2019), #29 in the World’s Top 100 Women Execs by Yahoo and HERoes (2019), one of Top 50 Women to Watch (2019) by Cranfield University, #EMRoleModels19 Top 100 Ethnic Minority Executives (2019), Innovate Finance Women in Fintech Powerlist (2019-18), one of the #TechWomen100 (2019), as 'Business Role Model of the Year' by the Women in IT Awards & Amazon (2019), by the Lloyds Banking Group Top 100 BAME Role Models List (2019, 2018) as a 'Global Champion' (#60) of the Top 100 Executive #FTHERoes18 by the Financial Times (2018) and awarded an Honorary Doctorate from De Montfort University (2018) for her ‘outstanding services to Business’.

She was honoured at the House of Lords (UK), at the NRI Pride of India World Summit (2017) for 'Making India Proud'. Bijna is credited as one of the Top 50 Visionary Young Leaders in Business, by Henley Business School (2017), one of 35 leading British Businesswomen under 35, by Management Today, Accenture and The Telegraph (2015) and has received recognition with 15 further honours including the National Diversity Awards (2012) and the Asian Women of Achievement Awards (2010). Bijna is also the International Women’s Day Young Achiever of the Year (2006).

Bijna is a Fellow of the Royal Society of Arts, Manufactures and Commerce (FRSA), and an alumnus of Oriel College, University of Oxford and Leicester Castle Business School, De Montfort University.

Tosin is also an experienced and accomplished public speaker on a range of topics including leadership, career progression and diversity & inclusion.
 

Tosin is an Advisory Board member at the Business School of Sussex University and is a NED for Badminton England.

Married with three children, John has been a qualified karate instructor since 2011 and teaches a class of around 30 students of all ages and abilities every weekend.

title: Executive Director
summary:
I am an accomplished leader, with consulting, industry and regulatory experience. I am expert in strategic, operational and financial planning, building multi-location teams and achieving consensus across stakeholders.

I started my career in Big 4 audit, quickly moving to advisory projects for top-tier and mid-sized retail banks, building societies and regulators. I specialised in the unwind of complex financial instrument portfolios and gained an 18 month secondment to the Bank of England to perform a key role in active contingency planning for potential failures of UK banks. I subsequently moved in-house to Morgan Stanley, where I later led the firm's European activities to plan for severe financial stress or failure.  I  now focus on corporate entity structure. 

My role focuses on change management and strategic implementation. I am expert in simplifying complexity and use emotional intelligence to lead teams and stakeholders through periods of change and transformation.  I draw on strengths in multi-disciplinary collaboration, consensus building, constructive challenge, exceptional organisation skills and clear communication to help the business implement challenging projects.  

While my career to date has been working at or for (as a consultant) large firms, within those I have founded and grown teams, including co-founding and leading and advisory team at Deloitte and growing a team at Morgan Stanley 50% by headcount.

My key strengths are:

- Structured, logical thinking: skilled at taking complex concepts and distilling them into clearly understandable explanations and ideas; I apply this to solve problems effectively and efficiently

- Clear communication, both written and spoken, enabling effective collaboration and challenge from stakeholders: I have applied this to support both the development of my team through to presentation to Board and Committee level governance.  I have substantial experience of presenting at key governance committees, including Operating Committees, Risk and Audit Committees and Boards.

- Lead with empathy: I have successfully built strong multi-disciplinary teams, including across cultures

- Very organised and efficient: I am highly productive and have a demonstrated ability to direct implementation projects in an efficient, collaborative and strategic manner

- Financial literacy: I am a Chartered Accountant (Fellow Chartered Accountant, FCA) and have a deep understanding of capital, liquidity and funding.

title: Managing Director, European Head of Banks and Diversified Financials Research
summary:
Magdalena Stoklosa is the European Head of Banks Research at Morgan Stanley. She is noted for her work on Emerging Markets banks development prior to Global Financial Crisis and views on reshaping of the European Banks. Magdalena has advised on banks for seventeen years focusing on structural long term profitability in the banking sector, the effect of regulatory shifts on banks, innovation and ESG inclusion in the business models. For the last seven years, she has been chairing Morgan Stanley’s European Financials Conference in London, one of the largest investment events in Financials in Europe.

She also sits on the European Central Bank’s Macro-Prudential and Financial Stability Group and on the European Central Bank’s Banking Supervision Market Contact Group. Her work has been quoted by the Economist, Financial Times in the UK and Handelsblatt in Germany among others. Her views on the European financials can also be found on Bloomberg and CNBC.


Prior to Morgan Stanley she worked at JPMorgan, Merill Lynch and KPMG.

Magdalena was also a Morgan Stanley UK Pension Plan Trustee and a member of the Morgan Stanley’s European Diversity Action Council. 

Magdalena has been educated at Box Hill School and the University of Maryland University College, where she won the Robert Bosch Foundation Scholarship. She is a CFA charterholder. 

Magdalena resides (normally) in London, with her family and three children.
